(ABSTRACT) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(This memo establishes naming conventions, metadata requirements, and) show newline
(scope rules for documentation in the Library of Cyberspace. We adopt) show newline
(IETF RFC format for technical compatibility while using "memo" as our) show newline
(vernacular.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
(STATUS OF THIS MEMO) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(This document is an Informational memo for the Library of Cyberspace) show newline
(community. It establishes conventions for penning memos.) show newline
() show newline
(Distribution of this memo is unlimited.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
(MOTIVATION) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(The IETF's "Request for Comments" name reflects a historical process we) show newline
(don't share.[^h1] We don't request comments—we record decisions. But) show newline
(the RFC format is well-understood and serves our needs.) show newline
() show newline
(The compromise: RFC format externally, "memo" internally.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(    "I penned a memo on wormholes"     < what we say) show newline
(    "See Memo-041"                       < how we cite) show newline
() show newline
([^h1]: Historical: The first RFC \(Memo-1, April 1969\) was literally a) show newline
(request for comments on host software. The name stuck. Fifty-seven years) show newline
(later, nobody requests comments—they publish specifications.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
